    "description": "Diyapaththugama Vidanalage Kumara Samarasinghe and others Vs The Hon. Attorney General before Hon. P. Kumararatnam, J.",
    "url_metadata": "https://courtofappeal.lk/?page_id=13130",
    "lang": "en",
    "url_pdf": "https://courtofappeal.lk/?melsta_doc_download=1&doc_id=3a8a1abd-7cf8-4775-a804-2ba9cab2b33f&filename=Court%20of%20Appeal%20JUDGMENT%20-%20HCC-0139-142.2020.pdf.pdf",
    "parties": "Diyapaththugama Vidanalage Kumara Samarasinghe and others Vs The Hon. Attorney General",
    "judgement_by": "Hon. P. Kumararatnam, J.",
    "keywords": "Eye witness. \u2022 Contradictions and Omissions",
    "legistation": "The Penal Code.",
    "chunk_id": "2025-12-03-CA-HCC--0139-142-2020-0007",
    "chunk_index": 7,
    "language": "en",
    "md5": "52e4d39f6f2f427b6a63af9afacb5ba9",
    "chunk_size_bytes": 1979,
    "chunk_text": "Considering the contradictions, omissions and the passage of time after the\n\nincident, a reasonable court cannot expect hundred percent accurate\n\nevidence from a witness. The Appellate Courts have repeatedly endorsed this\n\nJustice Thakkar in Bhoginbhai Hirigibhai v State of Gujarat 1983 AIR SC\n\n753 stated:\n\n\u201cDiscrepancies which do not go to the matter and shake the basic version\n\nof the witnesses therefore cannot be annexed with undue importance. More\n\nso when the all-important probabilities-factor echoes in favour of the\n\nversion narrated by the witnesses.\u201d\n\nThe learned High Court Judge in his judgment at pages 286-288 had\n\nconsidered the omissions highlighted and contradictions marked, and had\n\narrived at the finding that the said commissions and contradictions do not\n\ngo to the core of the case.\n\nI too agree with the learned High Court Judge that the omissions and\n\ncontradictions highlighted by the Appellants do not go to the root of the\n\nprosecution\u2019s case.\n\nThe learned High Court Judge adhering to the Section 283 of the Criminal\n\nProcedure Code Act No. 15 of 1979, had correctly evaluated the evidence\n\npresented by both sides and delivered the judgment. In the Judgment, the\n\nlearned High Court Judge had very correctly analysed the evidence presented\n\nby the prosecution and the defence.\n\nConsidering all appeal grounds advanced by the Appellants in this case, I\n\nconclude that none of the grounds have any merits.\n\nCA/HCC/0139-142/2020\n\n11 | P a g e\n\nConsidering the evidence led at the trial, I am of the view that there are no\n\nreasons to interfere with the judgment of the learned High Court Judge of\n\nKalutara. For the reasons stated above, I affirm the conviction and the\n\nsentence imposed on the Appellants.\n\nThe appeal is dismissed.\n\nThe Registrar is directed to send this judgment to the High Court of Kalutara\n\nalong with the original Case record.\n\nJUDGE OF THE COURT OF APPEAL\n\nR. P. Hettiarachchi, J\n\nI agree\n\nJUDGE OF THE COURT OF APPEAL"
