    "chunk_text": "vacancies to accommodate all the petitioners, even at this juncture.\n\n11. It is common ground that the petitioners have applied for the respective\n\nposts and faced an interview in or around 2020. The priority list based\n\ndue to an intervening Circular 01/2020, all recruitments had been\n\nsuspended. In this backdrop, though interviews were so held and a\n\npriority list compiled, no recruitments were in fact made based on the\n\nsame.\n\n12. Accordingly, the position of the respondents is:\n\na. that the petitioners are not entitled to any relief arising from the\n\nabandoned recruitment process, as its abandonment has not\n\nbeen challenged and no relief has been sought in that regard;\n\nb. that the petitioners cannot have a legitimate expectation to be\n\nappointed to the posts merely by participating in the recruitment\n\nprocess;\n\nWRT/0127/20\n\nPage 44 of 56\n\nc. that paragraph 12 of the letters of appointment does not/cannot\n\ngive rise to a legitimate expectation of permanent employment\n\nwithin the Department of Archaeology;\n\nd. that the petitioners do have a legal right enforceable in public law\n\nto be reinstated to service in terms of the letters of appointment\n\nmarked P1 \u2013 P394; and\n\ne. that the Public Administration Circulars marked P-4(i) and P-4(ii)\n\nare not applicable to the petitioners\u2019 circumstances.\n\n13. In view of Circular No. 01/2020 (5R-1), the interview process and\n\nrecruitments were all stalled and suspended. There onwards,\n\nrecruitments for the Primary Grades (PL(1), PL(2) and PL(3)) in all\n\ngovernment public institutions were suspended. Then, by virtue of\n\nCircular No. 02/2020 (5R-2), such recruitments to the Primary Grade\n\nwas carried out exclusively through the newly established Multi-Purpose\n\nDevelopment Task Force. In these circumstances, the petitioners who\n\nwere successful in the 2020 interviews were not issued with the\n\ninterview results or marks. The entire process was suspended. In the\n\ninterim, the periods of contract of the petitioners were all determined\n\nwith the lapse of time."
