    "chunk_text": "it, a sudden change of policy has certainly denied and violated the\n\nlegitimate expectation of the petitioners, particularly those 98\n\npetitioners who were successful at the interviews. The said circular No.\n\nfide. In the absence of any express rationale or reason, it appears to be\n\nso implemented either to deliberately prevent the petitioners from being\n\neligible or for some other extraneous reason. Even if it may not be\n\nexpress malice in acting so, there is, in the least, malice in law, which,\n\naccording to \u2018Principles of Administrative Law\u2019 by Jain and Jain (8th Ed.,\n\nat page 594), is as follows,\n\n\u201cMala fide exercise of power does not necessarily imply any moral turpitude as a matter of law. It only means that the statutory power is exercised for purposes foreign to those for which the law intended.\u201d [emphasis added]. Then also, Wade & Forsyth in \u2018Administrative Law\u2019 (11th Ed., at page\n\n354) where the author states as follows,\n\nWRT/0127/20\n\nPage 54 of 56\n\nIt is extremely rare for public authorities to be found guilty of intentional dishonesty: normally they are found to have erred, if at all, by ignorance or misunderstanding. Yet the courts constantly accuse them of bad faith merely because they have acted unreasonably or on improper grounds. Again and again it is laid down that powers must be exercised reasonably and in good faith. But in this context \u2018in good faith\u2019 means merely \u2018for legitimate reasons\u2019. Contrary to the natural sense of the words, they impute no moral obliquity.\u201d [emphasis added].\n\nThen at page 355,\n\n\u201cAnd Lord Greene MR\u2026treated bad faith as interchangeable with unreasonableness and extraneous considerations. Bad faith therefore scarcely has an independent existence as a distinct ground of invalidity.\u201d [emphasis added]. 30. Accordingly, on the one hand, the 98 petitioners who had a legitimate\n\nexpectation of being recruited has been denied and their expectations\n\nviolated. Similarly, the decision to change the policy by Circular No."
